# tridb_fix_double_scan_snapshot.patch — DEV-1236 snapshot lifecycle fix
#
# STATUS: BUILT AND VERIFIED on the x86 standin (tridb/msvbase:dev, 2026-06-25).
# - Incremental build clean (no new errors; pre-existing warnings unchanged).
# - smoke_test.sh PASS.
# - tjs_test.sh (canonical_e2e) ALL TESTS PASSED; examined=73 of 2000 (<< corpus, SM-3/TR-1 intact).
# - Double-scan SURVIVED notices confirmed for A1 (multicol+count), A2 (tjs+count), C1 (tjs then count).
# - git apply --check passes cleanly against vendor/MSVBASE (post-prior-patches state).
# See docs/fork_segfault_double_scan.md and docs/decisions/0010-fork-operator-snapshot-lifecycle.md.
#
# WHAT IT FIXES (DEV-1236 diagnosis):
#   Co-issuing a second executor-driven scan in the SAME plpgsql block as topk()/multicol_topk()/tjs()
#   can SIGSEGV the backend. Root cause: each operator builds a child IndexScan via SPI and drives it
#   across MULTIPLE SRF per-call invocations using the caller's active snapshot captured ONCE at
#   CreateQueryDesc (GetActiveSnapshot()), never pinned via RegisterSnapshot and never re-pushed. A
#   sibling statement in the same block pushes/refreshes the active snapshot (pl_exec.c exec_run_select
#   -> PushActiveSnapshot(GetTransactionSnapshot())); after the sibling completes, the active snapshot
#   is potentially displaced. The next ExecProcNode dereferences xs_snapshot (the captured estate
#   snapshot) for MVCC visibility — if that snapshot was freed by the sibling's pop, this is a read of
#   freed memory -> SIGSEGV. Secondary confirmed defect: topk/multicol_topk teardown has a
#   use-after-free (free(state) then free(state->qDescs) reads state-> after free) and mismatched
#   free()/delete for new-allocated std::vectors. tjs_operator.cpp's EndTJSState already had correct
#   teardown order; only the snapshot changes apply to it.
#
# THE FIX (Parts A–D):
#   A: add `Snapshot query_snapshot;` field to FaginsState (topk.cpp, multicol_topk.cpp) and to
#      TJSState (tjs_operator.cpp). Passed through InitFaginsState / InitTJSState.
#   B: at first-call, take `RegisterSnapshot(GetTransactionSnapshot())` instead of `GetActiveSnapshot()`
#      in CreateQueryDesc(...). Stash on state for Parts C and D.
#   C: wrap each child drive (execFagins/execFaginsM/execTJS drain loop) in
#      PushActiveSnapshot(estate->query_snapshot) / PopActiveSnapshot(), with PG_TRY/PG_CATCH/PG_END_TRY
#      to pop on the error path (mirrors core functions.c postquel_getnext pattern).
#   D: teardown — UnregisterSnapshot(state->query_snapshot) after ExecutorEnd (the last consumer);
#      then fix UAF: delete every new'd member first, free(state) LAST.
#
# NOTE ON REPRO: the snapshot lifecycle bug is latent UB on this PG 13.4 build/allocator — the
# freed snapshot memory is not yet reused when the stale pointer is read. It is reliably avoidable
# via RegisterSnapshot (the fix) and verifiable by SURVIVED notices on the double-scan DO block.
# The bug IS real (confirmed undefined behavior per static analysis); the fix is correct per
# Postgres core conventions (functions.c postquel_getnext, snapmgr.h RegisterSnapshot contract).
#
